SIMPLE: flotation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flotation
<hw>Flo*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>flottation</ets> a floating, <ets>flottaison</ets> water line, fr.
<ets>flotter</ets> to float. See <er>Flotilla</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act, process, or state of floating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The science of floating bodies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com. & Finance)</fld> <def>Act of financing, or
floating, a commercial venture or an issue of bonds, stock, or the
like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Center of flotation</b></col>. <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The center of any given plane of flotation.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>More commonly, the middle of the length of the load
water line.</cd> <au>Rankine.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Plane of
flotation</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Line of
flotation</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the plane or line in which the
horizontal surface of a fluid cuts a body floating in it. See
<er>Bearing</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 9 <sd>(c)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Surface
of flotation</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>the imaginary
surface which all the planes of flotation touch when a vessel rolls or
pitches; the envelope of all such planes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flotation process</ent>⟦br⟧
